node.title: Can England end Australia's run at Women's Cricket World Cup?
node.description: Australia and England captains both confident ahead of Cricket World Cup showdown in Christchurch.

node.title: Transcript: H.R. McMaster on "Face the Nation"
node.description: The following is a transcript of an interview with H.R. McMaster, former national security adviser in the Trump White House and a CBS News contributor, that aired Sunday, April 3, 2022, on "Face the Nation."

node.title: "Seinfeld" actress Estelle Harris dies at age 93
node.description: Harris also voiced Mrs. Potato Head in the "Toy Story" franchise.

node.title: Rock is America's favorite music, just not among young people
node.description: It's in third place for adults under 30 years of age, behind hip hop and pop.

node.title: Transcript: Rep. Jamie Raskin on "Face the Nation"
node.description: The following is a transcript of an interview with Democratic Rep. Jamie Raskin of Maryland that aired Sunday, April 3, 2022, on "Face the Nation."

node.title: Transcript: Fiona Hill on "Face the Nation"
node.description: The following is a transcript of an interview with Fiona Hill, the former senior director for European and Russian affairs on the National Security Council during the Trump administration, that aired Sunday, April 3, 2022, on "Face the Nation."

node.title: Transcript: New York Mayor Eric Adams on "Face the Nation"
node.description: The following is a transcript of an interview with New York City Mayor Eric Adams that aired Sunday, April 3, 2022, on "Face the Nation."

node.title: Jon Batiste, Suleika Jaouad announce they were secretly married
node.description: The bandleader of "The Late Show with Stephen Colbert" and the bestselling author of "Between Two Kingdoms" reveal they secretly wed in February on the eve of her bone marrow transplant.

node.title: Maren Morris on how she became fearless
node.description: The country music star talks about her new album, "Humble Quest," and what the past two years – from the pandemic to the birth of her son to social media trolls – have taught her about courage and humility.

node.title: Transcript: Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy on "Face the Nation"
node.description: The following is a transcript of an interview with Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy airing Sunday, April 3, 2022, on "Face the Nation."

node.title: Zelenskyy accuses Russia of genocide for alleged atrocities in Ukraine
node.description: The Ukrainian leader said Russia's invasion​, now in its sixth week, is about "the destruction and extermination" of the more than 100 nationalities in his country.

node.title: Charles M. Blow on "The Slap" as a cultural Rorschach test
node.description: The New York Times columnist examines the myriad takes about Will Smith's physical and verbal confrontation against comedian Chris Rock during the Academy Awards broadcast.

node.title: Jon Batiste on the healing power of music and love
node.description: The same day the "Late Show with Stephen Colbert" bandleader received 11 Grammy nominations, the love of his life began chemo for her second battle with cancer. Jon Batiste and author Suleika Jaouad talk about how they met adversity with an act of defiance.

node.title: Viva Ann-Margret!
node.description: The actress and singer who came to fame singing "Bye Bye Birdie" isn't ready to say farewell just yet. She talks about her transcendent six-decade career, from her status as a sex symbol, to becoming a Hollywood grand dame.

node.title: Redefining soul food and the history of American cuisine
node.description: African Americans have had an extraordinarily important, yet little understood, impact on American cuisine, a history continually expanded upon by Black chefs, and explored in a NYC exhibit, "African/American: Making the Nation's Table."

node.title: First sister Valerie Biden Owens
node.description: In her memoir, "Growing Up Biden," Joe Biden's younger sister writes about her family's story of tragedy; running most of her brother's political campaigns; and why she believes President Biden is the right person at the right time for the job.

node.title: The blurred lines surrounding music copyrights
node.description: Song composition has become an increasingly disharmonious area of litigation, as more and more songwriters are being taken to court when two songs share a melody, some chords, or even just a vibe.

node.title: What is Putin's endgame now?
node.description: Just over five weeks into Russia's stalled war in Ukraine, what is clear is that it will end in a negotiated settlement – but to whose advantage? Retired Gen. David Petraeus discusses what Russia hopes to achieve by concentrating its firepower on the eastern part of the country.

node.title: 6 dead and at least 9 injured in shooting in Sacramento, police say
node.description: Police in California say six people are dead and at least nine others have been injured after a shooting in downtown Sacramento.

node.title: Ukraine documents alleged atrocities by retreating Russians
node.description: Ukrainian troops are finding brutalized bodies and widespread destruction in suburbs of the capital as Russian soldiers withdraw.

node.title: Ann-Margret
node.description: Twice nominated for an Academy Award, the actress and singer came to fame in such musical hits as "Bye Bye Birdie" and "Viva Las Vegas," before turning in acclaimed dramatic performances in such films as "The Cincinnati Kid" and "Carnal Knowledge."

node.title: Ukraine sees openings as Russians focus on besieged Mariupol
node.description: Ukraine's president said Russia's obsession with capturing a key port city had left its forces weakened and created opportunities for his military.

node.title: Insurance Council calls for NZ to invest in climate change mitigation measures
node.description: The council's chief executive, Tim Grafton, says recent flooding events show the country cannot just keep repairing flooded areas.

node.title: Hungarians vote on 12-year rule in tight ballot overshadowed by Ukraine war
node.description: The odds are slightly in favour of Hungary's nationalist Prime Minister Viktor Orban, extending his 12-year rule in today's election, helped by his government's firm control over state media.

node.title: Ukraine forces retake areas north of Kyiv as Russians look eastward
node.description: Ukrainian forces have advanced into areas north of Kyiv as Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky accuses departing Russian soldiers of leaving behind mines.

node.title: Moana Jackson tangi: Thousands pay their respects
node.description: Renowned constitutional expert and Māori advocate Dr Moana Jackson has been laid to rest at Matahiwi marae in Hawke's Bay.

node.title: Covid-19: More than half of Healthline calls abandoned during Delta outbreak
node.description: Some Covid-19 Healthline callers were on hold for more than three hours at the start of the Delta outbreak, data reveals.

node.title: Australia triumph in Women's Cricket World Cup
node.description: Australia have beaten the defending champions, England, by 71 runs in Christchurch.

node.title: Firefighters battle Southland fire: 'These guys are doing it hard out there'
node.description: A major fire at Awarua, south of Invercargill, is burning through about 1000 hectares of mānuka scrub and peat soils in the drought-stricken region.

node.title: The Battle of Auckland - big brother gets the win, but still sees red
node.description: Analysis - Despite a dominant performance, the Blues and Moana Pasifika rivalry promises to be one of the biggest features of Super Rugby, writes Jamie Wall. Video
